<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,686,713]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
An 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Girard" authorityYear="1857" box="[368,491,687,713]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,491,687,713]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Oligosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a squarish mid-body cross-section; opaque, divided palpebral disc; a prominent tear-drop mark beneath each eye; iris light brown to orange; mid-body scale rows 37–44; ventral scale rows 88–97; eye diameter &lt;distance from the eye to mouth; adult SVL ≥ 
<quantity box="[843,925,759,785]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="90.0">90 mm</quantity>
; dorsal markings dominated by pale blotches or mottling; belly cream and markings form broad blotching. Distinguished from similar congeners (which share both the squarish body cross-section and the tear-drop subocular marking) as follows: 
<taxonomicName authority="(Robb)" authorityName="Robb" baseAuthorityName="Robb" baseAuthorityYear="1970" box="[1113,1257,831,858]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="alani">
<emphasis box="[1113,1171,831,857]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">alani</emphasis>
(Robb)
</taxonomicName>
has a black iris, much larger dorsal blotches and is bulkier, up to 
<quantity box="[701,795,867,893]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.42" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="142.0">142 mm</quantity>
SVL; 
<emphasis box="[870,1000,868,893]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">macgregori</emphasis>
(Robb) has longitudinal streaks on the dorsum and a uniform belly; 
<emphasis box="[482,577,904,929]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">ornatum</emphasis>
(Gray) is much smaller (SVL usually &lt;
<quantity box="[1037,1121,903,929]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="80.0">80 mm</quantity>
), usually has a yellow belly and usually has a tapering pale dorso-lateral stripe; 
<taxonomicName box="[723,911,939,965]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pachysomaticum">
<emphasis box="[723,911,939,965]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">pachysomaticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 32–36 mid-body scale rows, 72–88 ventral scale rows, dorsal and ventral patterns dominated by dark flecks, and a larger eye (diameter&gt; distance from eye to mouth); 
<taxonomicName authority="(Patterson, Hitchmough &amp; Chapple)" authorityName="Patterson, Hitchmough &amp; Chapple" baseAuthorityName="Patterson, Hitchmough &amp; Chapple" box="[248,754,1011,1038]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roimata">
<emphasis box="[248,336,1012,1037]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">roimata</emphasis>
(Patterson, Hitchmough &amp; Chapple)
</taxonomicName>
(sympatric) is much smaller at up to 
<quantity box="[1184,1264,1010,1037]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="65.0">65 mm</quantity>
SVL, has only 32–34 mid-body scale rows and 1 primary temporal scale (versus 
<quantity box="[901,945,1047,1073]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
<taxonomicName box="[953,1026,1047,1073]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oliveri">
<emphasis box="[953,1026,1047,1073]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">oliveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Chapple, Patterson, Gleeson, Daugherty &amp; Ritchie" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[1052,1125,1048,1073]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="townsi">
<emphasis box="[1052,1125,1048,1073]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">townsi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
usually has only 1 primary temporal scale and few ventral markings; and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hardy" baseAuthorityYear="1977" box="[666,772,1083,1109]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="whitakeri">
<emphasis box="[666,772,1083,1109]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">whitakeri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a dark-brown iris, yellow-orange venter and dorsal and ventral patterns of dark flecks.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1155,1181]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Etymology.</emphasis>
McCann named the species for Dr W.R.B. Oliver (
<date box="[917,1048,1154,1181]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" value="1883" valueMax="1957">1883–1957</date>
), former director of the Dominion Museum (now Museum of 
<collectingCountry box="[465,616,1191,1217]" name="New Zealand" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
/Te Papa Tongarewa) in 
<collectingRegion box="[898,1025,1191,1217]" country="New Zealand" name="Wellington" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Wellington</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1038,1194,1191,1217]" name="New Zealand" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
. The established vernacular name ‘marbled skink’ should ideally remain with this taxon as it is strongly associated with the name 
<taxonomicName box="[1363,1436,1227,1253]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oliveri">
<emphasis box="[1363,1436,1227,1253]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">oliveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and aptly describes the characteristic colour pattern of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1298,1325]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the Poor Knights Islands off the east coast of 
<collectingRegion box="[1065,1179,1299,1325]" country="New Zealand" name="Northland" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Northland</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1192,1285,1299,1325]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1525,1550]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,301,1506]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,301,1506]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Map of upper North Island of New Zealand showing distribution records for extant populations of the four members of the Oligosoma oliveri species-complex. Bold outline = maximum expanse of land during the Otira Glaciation 18,000–20,000 years ago; thin outline = present extent of land; dotted line = former path of Waikato River; blue shading = suggested former distributional extent of O. townsi in this region; pink shading = suggested former distributional extent of O. pachysomaticum in this region." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3516817" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3516817/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Figure 1</figureCitation>
) where it has been recorded from seven islets including Tawhiti Rahi I., Aorangi I., Motu Kapiti I., Archway I., Stack ‘A’, Stack ‘B’, and Stack ‘C’ (
<tableCitation box="[369,454,1371,1397]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[151,239,694,718]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Extant populations of the Oligosoma oliveri species-complex. Data from Towns (1999), Chapple et al. (2008b) and van Winkle et al. (2018)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/D8CF9C87FFCAFF26FF59FD3E608DF1B7" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" tableUuid="D8CF9C87FFCAFF26FF59FD3E608DF1B7">Table 1</tableCitation>
; 
