<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,300,1407,1433]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Ecology.</emphasis>
Lives primarily among leaf litter on the floor of coastal forest and scrub, utilizing a range of cover objects and sea bird burrows as retreat sites, and is crepuscular with peaks of activity after dusk and before dawn. Gravid females occasionally bask but the species is normally otherwise inactive by day. Co-exists in this habitat with two much smaller skinks, i.e. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Chapple, Patterson, Bell &amp; Daugherty)" authorityName="Chapple, Patterson, Bell &amp; Daugherty" baseAuthorityName="Chapple, Patterson, Bell &amp; Daugherty" baseAuthorityYear="2008" box="[540,1192,1515,1542]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="hardyi">
<emphasis box="[540,742,1515,1541]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Oligosoma hardyi</emphasis>
(Chapple, Patterson, Bell &amp; Daugherty)
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[1207,1287,1515,1541]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="62.0">62 mm</quantity>
SVL) and 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="roimata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">O. roimata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<quantity box="[254,334,1550,1577]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" unit="mm" value="65.0">65 mm</quantity>
SVL) (
<bibRefCitation author="Towns, D. R." box="[417,560,1551,1577]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" refId="ref6348" refString="Towns, D. R. (1999) Cyclodina spp. skink recovery plan, 1999 - 2004. New Zealand Department of Conservation, Wellington, 69 pp. Available from: https: // www. doc. govt. nz / Documents / conservation / native-animals / reptiles-and-frogs / Cyclodinaskinkrecoveryplan. pdf (Accessed 22 Oct. 2019)" type="book" year="1999">Towns 1999</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Whitaker, A. H." box="[571,741,1551,1577]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="623 - 651" refId="ref6724" refString="Whitaker, A. H. (1968) The lizards of the Poor Knights Islands, New Zealand. New Zealand Journal of Science, 11, 623 - 651." type="journal article" year="1968">Whitaker 1968</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="van Winkle, D. &amp; Baling, M. &amp; Hitchmough, R." box="[753,1012,1551,1577]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" refId="ref6411" refString="van Winkle, D., Baling, M. &amp; Hitchmough, R. (2018) Reptiles and amphibians of New Zealand, a field guide. Auckland University Press, Auckland, 366 pp." type="book" year="2018">
van Winkle 
<emphasis box="[888,944,1551,1577]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,371,1586,1613]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Biogeography.</emphasis>
The Poor Knights Islands are the remnants of a ten million year old rhyolite volcano that has been separated from the mainland since the Pliocene, between 1–2 million years ago (
<bibRefCitation author="Hayward, B. W." box="[1110,1281,1623,1649]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="23 - 37" refId="ref5803" refString="Hayward, B. W. (1991) Geology and geomorphology of the Poor Knights Islands, northern New Zealand. Tane, 33, 23 - 37. Available from: http: // www. thebookshelf. auckland. ac. nz / docs / Tane / Tane- 33 / 5 % 20 Geology % 20 and % 20 geomorphology. pdf (Accessed 22 Oct. 2019)" type="journal article" year="1991">Hayward 1991</bibRefCitation>
). Members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[192,395,1659,1685]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oliveri">
<emphasis box="[192,395,1659,1685]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Oligosoma oliveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species-complex are vulnerable to extremes of temperature and hydration, experiencing high levels of cutaneous body water loss (
<bibRefCitation author="Towns, D. R." box="[562,702,1695,1721]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" refId="ref6348" refString="Towns, D. R. (1999) Cyclodina spp. skink recovery plan, 1999 - 2004. New Zealand Department of Conservation, Wellington, 69 pp. Available from: https: // www. doc. govt. nz / Documents / conservation / native-animals / reptiles-and-frogs / Cyclodinaskinkrecoveryplan. pdf (Accessed 22 Oct. 2019)" type="book" year="1999">Towns 1999</bibRefCitation>
) and so are unlikely to be effective oversea rafters. This indicates that 
<taxonomicName box="[200,307,1731,1757]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oliveri">
<emphasis box="[200,307,1731,1757]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">O. oliveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has likely been isolated on these islands for between 1–2 million years.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,329,1767,1793]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Phylogeny.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Chapple, D. G. &amp; Daugherty, C. H. &amp; Ritchie, P. A." box="[338,586,1767,1793]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="129 - 146" refId="ref5369" refString="Chapple, D. G., Daugherty, C. H. &amp; Ritchie, P. A. (2008 a) Comparative phylogeography reveals pre-decline population structure of New Zealand Cyclodina (Reptilia: Scincidae) species, Biological Journal of the Linnean Society, 95 (2), 129 - 146 https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1095 - 8312.2008.01062. x" type="journal article" year="2008">
Chapple 
<emphasis box="[439,490,1767,1793]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">et al</emphasis>
. (2008a
</bibRefCitation>
, b) present phylogenetic reconstructions based on analysis of the sequence differentiation observed among three mitochondrial genes (i.e. 600 base pairs of ND2, 850 base pairs of ND4, 700 base pairs of Cytochrome b). The calibration they employed indicated a split between 
<taxonomicName box="[1145,1350,1839,1865]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oliveri">
<emphasis box="[1145,1350,1839,1865]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Oligosoma oliveri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Oligosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pachysomaticum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">O. pachysomaticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of between 1.07–1.43 million years ago, which coincides with the estimated isolation of the Poor Knights Islands themselves (see ‘Biogeography’, above).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="391" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,614,2009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1947,1973]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391">Remarks.</emphasis>
The taxonomic definition is returned to its original concept, i.e. that of 
<bibRefCitation author="McCann, C." box="[1138,1319,1946,1973]" pageId="2" pageNumber="391" pagination="1 - 127" refId="ref6095" refString="McCann, C. (1955) The lizards of New Zealand. Gekkonidae and Scincidae. Dominion Museum Bulletin, 17, 1 - 127." type="journal article" year="1955">McCann (1955)</bibRefCitation>
, who provides a full morphological description.
</paragraph>
